Gantt Chart

Abstract

Limited credit history can prevent individuals from accessing fair and responsible lending opportunities. The Home Credit Default Risk dataset offers a rich set of features from multiple sources, enabling the prediction of loan repayment potential for such individuals. This project aims to develop a comprehensive pipeline that supports this goal by integrating structured data from diverse sources including previous applications, credit bureau reports, and transactional histories.

We have begun by consolidating datasets, handling missing values, encoding categorical features, and performing exploratory analysis to guide further processing. A preprocessing pipeline is under development to include feature engineering, scaling, outlier handling, and dimensionality reductionensuring the data is clean, interpretable, and ready for modeling.

We are currently evaluating various machine learning models such as Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost, and Support Vector Machines to establish a performance baseline. Given the inherent class imbalance in default prediction, we are focusing on metrics like ROC AUC, F1 Score, Gini Coefficient, and Precision-Recall AUC. LightGBM has shown early promise with strong separation between defaulters and non-defaulters.

Future steps include refining the pipeline with cross-validation, model ensembling, and hyperparameter tuning. While results are preliminary, this study is on track to deliver a scalable and interpretable solution that promotes financial inclusion through responsible credit assessment.

Dataset: Detailed Analysis and Understanding

Objective

The objective of this project is to predict whether a loan applicant will default on their loan. The dataset is provided by Home Credit and includes both static and behavioral data of clients from current and past loans. The main binary target is:

  • TARGET = 1: Client defaulted on the loan
  • TARGET = 0: Client repaid the loan

Dataset Overview

The dataset consists of multiple interrelated tables that collectively describe:

  • Client Demographics: such as age, gender, education level, and family status
  • Financial History: including income, employment, and housing information
  • Credit Behavior: repayment history, loan performance, and usage patterns
  • Loan Application Data: current and previous applications, requested and granted credit

The central dataset is application_train.csv (and application_test.csv for prediction). This contains one row per client loan application and includes the main target variable.

All other datasets supplement this primary data and are connected using two key identifiers:

  • SK_ID_CURR: Client ID links most tables to the main application table
  • SK_ID_PREV: Previous loan/application ID links time-series or behavioral data from past loans

Supporting datasets include:

  • bureau.csv and bureau_balance.csv: external credit history from other institutions
  • previous_application.csv: previous loans requested from Home Credit
  • POS_CASH_balance.csv: monthly status of POS/cash loans
  • installments_payments.csv: repayment behavior of past loans
  • credit_card_balance.csv: credit card balance and payment patterns

Together, these datasets allow for comprehensive feature engineering and modeling based on both static client characteristics and dynamic historical behavior.

application_train.csv / application_test.csv

These are the central datasets for the project, containing information about current loan applications. Each row corresponds to a single loan application by a client. The training file (application_train.csv) includes the target variable (TARGET), while the test file does not. These datasets include demographic, employment, financial, and housing-related attributes, serving as the base for merging and feature engineering from all other supporting tables.

bureau.csv

This file contains information about clients previous credits from external financial institutions, collected from the credit bureau. Each row represents one such past loan, and clients can have multiple records. It includes credit status (active, closed), types of loans, amounts, and durations. It is linked to the main dataset using the SK_ID_CURR key.

bureau_balance.csv

This dataset provides monthly balance information for each credit record listed in the bureau.csv file. It captures the monthly credit status (e.g., paid on time, overdue, closed) and spans multiple months per loan. It helps model repayment behavior over time and links to bureau.csv via the SK_ID_BUREAU key.

previous_application.csv

This dataset captures all previous loan applications submitted to Home Credit by clients, regardless of whether the application was approved or rejected. It includes information on loan types, status, requested amounts, and actual credit received. It is crucial for analyzing a clients past interactions with Home Credit and is linked to the main dataset using SK_ID_CURR.

POS_CASH_balance.csv

This table includes monthly snapshots of previously disbursed Point-of-Sale (POS) and cash loans issued by Home Credit. Each row corresponds to one month of a given loans status and remaining installments. It provides insight into payment behavior and the lifecycle of short-term credit products, and is connected via the SK_ID_PREV field.

installments_payments.csv

This dataset contains payment records for previous Home Credit loans, showing expected versus actual payments made per installment. It includes installment numbers, payment amounts, and payment dates. It helps model repayment reliability, especially identifying missed or late payments. It is linked using SK_ID_PREV.

credit_card_balance.csv

This dataset records the monthly balance and payment activity on Home Credit-issued credit cards. Similar to the POS data, it offers time-series records of balances, payments, and overdue days. It helps identify how responsibly a client manages their revolving credit and is connected through SK_ID_PREV.

HomeCredit_columns_description.csv

This is a metadata file containing descriptions of all columns across the datasets. It is essential for understanding the meaning and relevance of each feature, especially when dealing with abbreviations or engineered variables.

Algorithms & Metrics:

Machine Learning Algorithms:

Given the heterogeneity and complexity of the Home Credit Default Risk datasetwith its high dimensionality, missing values, and imbalanced classeswe plan to experiment with a variety of machine learning models before selecting the most robust one. Our baseline models will include Logistic Regression with L1 regularization, Random Forests, and Gradient Boosting Machines (e.g., XGBoost), which are well-suited for handling mixed feature types and non-linear patterns. We also aim to test Support Vector Machines (SVM) due to their effectiveness in high-dimensional spaces, as well as Neural Networks (MLPs) for their flexibility in modeling complex interactions. Ultimately, model selection will be based on empirical performance and interpretability.

Evaluation Metrics:

Given the imbalanced nature of the dataset, ROC AUC will be our primary evaluation metric, as it effectively captures the trade-off between sensitivity and specificity across different thresholds. We will also monitor the F1 score, which balances precision and recall, especially in scenarios where both false positives and false negatives carry consequences. Additional metrics include Balanced Accuracy (to account for class imbalance), Precision-Recall AUC, and the Gini Coefficient, a domain-specific metric commonly used in credit scoring. By comparing multiple models under these diverse metrics, we aim to ensure both predictive accuracy and practical relevance in real-world credit risk assessment.

Description of the Pipeline Steps:

Our project will implement a robust and modular machine learning pipeline using Scikit-learn, structured as follows:

Data Ingestion and Loading:

  • Load and inspect the main application data (application_train.csv) and associated datasets (e.g., bureau, previous applications, credit card balance).
  • Understand and visualize missing data, data types, and data distribution.

Data Merging and Feature Consolidation

  • Merge secondary datasets (e.g., bureau.csv, previous_application.csv) with the primary dataset using SK_ID_CURR as the key.
  • Aggregate features at the customer level where needed (e.g., total number of loans, average loan amount from bureau data).

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing

  • Handle missing values:
    • Drop columns with excessive missingness.
    • Impute remaining missing values using statistical methods (mean/median or KNN imputation).
  • Handle outliers (e.g., capping extreme values using quantile clipping).
  • Convert categorical variables:
    • Apply one-hot encoding to nominal categorical variables.
    • Use label encoding where appropriate.

Feature Engineering

  • Create domain-specific features (e.g., credit-to-income ratio, number of previous loans).
  • Generate interaction terms between key variables.
  • Standardize numerical features using StandardScaler.

Feature Selection

  • Use mutual information, correlation analysis, or model-based feature importance to select top N features.
  • Optionally, apply dimensionality reduction (e.g., PCA) for model comparison.

Model Building

  • Build a supervised classification model pipeline using Pipeline():
    Pipeline([
    ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('classifier', LogisticRegression())
])
  • Try multiple algorithms (Logistic Regression, KNN, Random Forest,XGBoost) and compare performance.
  • Hyperparameter tuning using GridSearchCV.
